# Exports at the bottom

In TypeScript files, define implementations first, then export from one block at the **bottom** of the file.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — inline exports scattered through the file
export function generatePerson() { ... }
export type RandomFn = () => number;

// ✅ GOOD — local definitions, exports at the bottom
function generatePerson() { ... }

type RandomFn = () => number;

export { generatePerson, type RandomFn };
```

## Rules

- Prefer a single `export { ... }` block as the last statement in the file.
- Use `export { type Foo }` (or a separate `export type { ... }` block) for types.
- Keep helpers and constants unexported unless they are part of the module’s public API.
- When adding new public symbols, add them to the bottom export block instead of adding new inline `export` keywords above.

## Exceptions

- **Default exports** only when a framework requires them (e.g. some config entry points). Still prefer named exports + bottom block when possible.
- **Barrel/re-export files** (`index.ts`) may use `export { X } from "./x"`; keep those re-exports grouped at the bottom too.
- **Generated files** — do not hand-edit; follow the generator’s format.

## When editing existing files

- Match the file’s current export style if the change is a one-line fix.
- When doing substantive edits to a file, migrate its exports to the bottom-of-file pattern.
